title: Iron-on 3D printed artworks - Proof of concept

description.text:
I was thinking about making my own t-shirt artwork eversince, but silkprinting needs much equipment that I didn't want to buy to just make two or tree shirts for my own...
So I invented another Idea: The 3D printable t-shirt (or textile) artwork. PLA will melt at about 60Â°C - fair enough to be ironed-on to any kind of fabric. I tested it with some bags I am sewing to organize my luggage for holiday... :)
edit 1: added some more critters to experiment with..

The process is relatively simple. You need the following materials and tools: Materials:
-electric iron (actually one with coal will work too... ;) )
-baking paper
-any kind of graphic to 3D print
-3D printer that is able to print soft PLA
-some soft PLA Artwork for Printing:
Any kind of 2D Graphic can be used. Use your preferred 3D-Software to create a solid file with the same thickness that your artwork should have (I use 0.20mm which works well for me).
Create an STL file, slice it and print it. The print will be one single layer thick. I print on glas directly - like this the printed "foil" can be removed with a sharp knifeblade. I used soft PLA for best results - it works with standard PLA but this will give a quite stiff T-Shirt ;) Ironing:
The Ironing process is fairly easy. Nevertheless, I recommend to make some tests/exercise first with some old fabric pieces or so...
  • Place your Artwork on the desired position
  • Cover with baking paper (this will prevent the artwork from being molten to your electric iron)
  • Heat up the Iron (I used heat level 2 of 3 on my Iron... works great... don't go to hot or your artwork will completely be molten into the fabric and will not stay that visible...)
  • Place iron on top of the artwork. Make sure it stays flat and in position. Press it down a few seconds.
  • Leave baking paper on the artwork until it cools down, then remove the paper.
    • Things left to test:
    I didn't do any machine washing tests so far and no wearing tests... it is just a proof of concept so far... perhaps you might want to leave me a comment if you gain some experience with it...
    Further Infos will follow... :)

title: Full color print module for Anet A8
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
These parts are designed to fix the ColorPod on a Anet A8 3d printer.

The CororPod converts a reprap style filament 3d printer to a full color powder printer.

The ColorPod is a device that extents a regular 3D printer with the capability of printing full color 3D models. The unit prints full color 3D objects by dispensing powder and colored liquid droplets. It creates a model in a heap of powder on the build plate. It can be used with most popular 3D printers.

Most parts where printed in PLA with the default cura settings including Brim and touching buildplate-support. layer height I used is 0.25mm. Part P2.stl needs to be very strong. For this part it is advised to double the shell thickness and bottom/top thickness.

In the video the colorpod is used on a similar Geeetech printer. I have not been able to test it on the Anet yet (sept 2017). If you have an Anet and live in the west of the Netherlands, you can help me.

More information at
http://www.spitstec.nl/colorpod
http://www.vouwbad.nl/colorpod/howto.html

Video at:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cIZFKcW97js

All parts are combined in their build position in the "anet-colorpod.stp" -file. Parts in this file can be used to adapt the design in a cad program.

To Colorpod needs two signals from the Anet main board. Two pictures show where you can find these signals on the original Anet main board. To make these connections you need fine soldering skills.

comments.text: In general, according to physics, acoustic horns increase the volume/area of a sound wave as it moves from the small entry port, through the expanding horn shape to exit at the larger opening. This wave of air constantly expands to fill the current amount of space as it moves through the horn which means the wave constantly expands to a larger wave as it travels. This is why blowing hard on a trumpet or yelling through a cone-shaped megaphone will be louder than the same person simply yelling. Shaping the expanding horn so that the internal size increases along a progressively more curved surface as it approaches the exit port will make the horn work better. You can increase the boost by doing two things. Make the exit opening even larger and/or make the horn longer.

title: Kettle-Pod - the tabletop camera arm
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Kettle-Pod is a camera extension arm for filming your tabletop.

It uses a kettle bell and rubber bands to hold a camera over your work area, without getting tripod legs in the frame. The heavy base allows you to move the Kettle-Pod anywhere on the desk.

The arm is counter-weighted using rubber bands. The counter-weight can be adjusted by adding/removing rubber bands and by moving the attachment point of the rubber bands.

You don't have to limit yourself to a kettle-bell; you can attach Kettle-Pod to pretty much anything with a round cross-section (36 mm OD max).

Parts list

Printed parts
  • 3× arm_coupler_open.stl
  • 2× arm_coupler_endcap.stl
  • 1× arm_coupler_rubberband.stl
  • 1× arm_coupler_pivot.stl
  • 1× base_pivot.stl
  • 1× base_knob.stl
  • (Optional) 1× base_knob_wrench.stl for tightening the knob.
  • (Optional) 1× mount_tripod.stl to mount cameras via the regular tripod screw.
  • (Optional) 1× mount_handlebar.stl to mount a GoPro/action camera using its bike handlebar mount.
Vitamins
  • 3× rods, 12 mm OD (thin-walled steel tube or dowel, or anything else). The length is up to you, but mine are 1 m long.
  • 1× kettle bell.
  • 1× hose clamp (around 27–51 mm).
  • 1× M8 bolt, 60 mm or longer (or cut some all-thread rod and Loctite an M8 nut onto it)
  • 2× M8 nuts.
  • 3× M3 screws, 15 mm or longer.
  • 6× M3 knurled inserts.
  • Some string.
  • 1× hook.
  • Some thick rubber bands.
  • (Optional) 1× 1/4-20 screw for the tripod mount.

Build instructions

  1. Push the M3 inserts into the small holes in arm_coupler_endcap.
  2. Slide the arm couplers onto the arms.
    • arm_coupler_pivot should be at the balance point of the rods.
    • arm_coupler_rubberband should be between the pivot and the ends of the rods.
    • arm_coupler_endcap goes on each end of the rods.
    • 'arm_coupler_open` gets spaced out between the other couplers to make the arm more rigid.
  3. Screw the mount you've chosen to the endcap opposite the rubber band coupler using the M3 screws.
  4. Use the hose clamp to fasten base_pivot to the handle of the kettle bell.
  5. Tie string around the base of the kettle bell's handle, and then hang the hook on the string. This lets the hook self-center on the kettle bell as it is being pulled.
  6. Attach the arm to the base using the M8 bolt and nut. Push the nut into the knob to make it easier to tighten it. Use the wrench to tighten it even more.
  7. Loop rubber bands around arm_coupler_rubberband and onto the hook.

Using Kettle-Pod

  1. Adjust the extension of the arm by sliding it along the pivot coupler.
  2. Attach your camera to the mount.
  3. Loosen the locking knob to allow the arm to pivot freely. Don't let your camera fall and hit the desk!
  4. Balance the arm by adjusting the counter-weight. You can add/remove rubber bands, and/or move the rubber band coupler along the arm.
  5. Once the arm is balanced, tighten the locking knob.

Notes:

I recommend printing these parts in PETG for strength and flexibility.

The only part that requires support is base_pivot.stl. All others are designed to print support-free.

title: The Ant (holder for 7 g.SAHARA EEG electrodes)

description.text:
An EEG electrodes holder for a basic 7-electrode EEG setup using g.SAHARA electrodes.
This is my entry in the Ars Electronica 2017 Br41n.IO hackathon, awarded the second place.
A result of ~6 hours of design, it is still quite rough around the edges, but a good starting point for further refinement. I have attached the STEP file if you want to play with it. The decorative legs are aligned with the electrode placement lines, so it is easy to add additional electrodes.
A big Thank You to the entire hackathon team, it was a lovely experience to be a part of! :)

Notes:

Print one of each. Turn the head, body and tail around to cut down on the need for supports.

Clean up the printed parts and connect the hinges using M4 screws and nuts. Add a drop of superglue onto the tightened nuts to prevent them from unscrewing. Place rubber bands on the pointy rubber band holders so the parts are pushed inwards toward the head.

In Fusion 360 I made an ellipsoid as a stand in for the more complex head shape—in the area of the electrodes it is a good-enough approximation considering the adaptive design with rubber bands. I then designed a simple holder for the g.SAHARA electrode, cloned it and placed it on the appropriate places on the head. I then built the ant body parts around these, creating the general look I was going for. In the end, I added hinges to hold everything together. The process is easiest to explain if you look at the video.

title: 163° Tweezers
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
They say necessity is the mother of invention. And while the necessity of these tweezers may not be apparent at first, watching a youtube clip of someone struggling for lack of a better tool, does get the creative juices flowing.

SerpaDesign is a youtuber who creates unique vivariums and his latest endeavor was to create a vivarium in a glass sphere with no visible opening, achieving a seamless look.

How he achieved this is actually pretty cool on it's own, but it did involve a lot of finagling to get all the plants and dirt in the right spot. This tool aims to facilitate the process of positioning the plants in the vivarium.

"How to Make a Terrarium Without An Opening"
https://youtu.be/bN_pT2664i0?t=23m33s

Required Supplies

-Superglue
-Ball-point pen spring (4mm X 24mm)
-10mm long section of filament (1.75mm or 2.85mm)

Instructions

Choose one of the STL files based on the filament diameter you prefer (1.75mm or 2.85mm). A 10mm section of filament can be used as a pin in the hinge of the tweezers. Or if you prefer you can use the pin that has been included in each of the models. Use super glue or a heating device such as a soldering iron to affix one of the ends of the pin inside the hinge. Be advised, securing both sides of the pin will render the hinge inoperable.

The hinge halves should align nicely in the grooves of the tweezer arms with the hinge part closest to the back. It can be fixed in position with superglue It will fit in both ways but I trust you'll be able to figure out if you're doing it wrong ;)

The spring in the hinge uses a standard ballpoint pen spring. 24mm long and 4mm diameter, although slight variations should work just as well. It can be pressure fit in the circular divots on the insides of each tweezer arm, which should keep it in place while using the tweezers.

When printing this you may want to use a lower percentage of infill to save on plastic. Also the tweezer arms are quite long but they will fit diagonally on a 200mm X 200mm bed if printed individually.

title: Nintendo Switch 35/55 Easy Stand made for VOEZ

description.text:
This stand for the Switch is very easy, quick and low material to print.
It can be used in both 35° and 55° orientation (the Switch kickstand is ~65°).

Print one at a time and adjust the scale +/- 1% if needed so the stands are just tight enough they don't fall off when the Switch is picked up. Position the stands at each end of the main body before the Joycons for best stability and to not block any buttons/cooling.

Bought a Switch yesterday, tried and immediately fell in love with VOEZ, quickly realized that when playing on a desk the angle is not very ergonomic, also banging away on the screen means the Joycon joint gets stressed. The 35° mode is what I think is the ideal angle to play VOEZ at a desk.

TIP: If playing on a slick surface like a glass desk, you can stick a piece of electrical tape on the bottom surface of each stand to give the plastic a higher grip surface.

Not having a lot of desk real estate, I often have to inconveniently switch between a keyboard and a graphics tablet, and sometimes an iPad when I'm drawing up something in 53's Paper app or the like.
In the past, this meant propping up the keyboard next to the printer, which was more than a bit tedious since I still sometimes had to use the board for a shortcut (I'll have to see about getting a number pad for that or some other custom option). Obviously this stand won't make using shortcut keys any less of a hassle (unless you glue it to your desk, or if someone remixes it to have spaces underneath for magnets--you have my sympathy for the former and my blessing for the latter). However, it will keep it from rudely sliding down and into whatever I'm working on while it's supposed to be out of the way.
Albeit I'd intended for this to let you stand the keyboard up tall-wise, this may not be a great option unless your particular version of this Dell keyboard lacks the number pad. Fortunately, thanks to the keys being an equal distance from the edge all the way around, you can balance it horizontally on one or print two and tuck it under your monitor.
More than anything, this was an excuse to get used to Sketchup a program that typically frustrates me on every level down to the very core of my being. I blame myself for being spoiled on more hand-holding programs (cough... Tinkercad... cough) and subsequently impatient with ones that don't.

description.text:
I have a diabetic dog that requires two insulin injections a day. Missing an injection is not good....giving a double dose can be fatal. I wanted something like a pill reminder but could find nothing commercially available for syringes( edit: Actually, just search for "syringe tray" and you will find them). I also looked for a simple plastic organizer tray but didn't find one with 7 slots.

This tray helps provide visual indication that an injection was given. Simply fill the tray at the beginning of the week and you can easily tell what shot is due. I also use a printed matrix with the day of the month as the columns and the medication as the row (she also needs eye drops).

The font for the lettering is "Minecraft Evenings" and was drawn as 3D text using Sketchup.

I've included the Designspark Mechanical file for modification, if someone likes. It's easy to split the text off of the top and import your own. If using Sketchup, be sure to save the new text as a Sketchup 2014 file. I couldn't get DSM to import the current version "sketchup" type file.

The tray bottom measures 191mm X 130mm X 19mm so it takes a while to print (over 9 hours for me). I tried to make the top press on but I had to use some glue to hold mine on.

They syringes are 3/10ml, U100 type.

description.text:
The answer to all the quadrocopter designs:

The HexaMicroFly !!!

This is the video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZvVWfrv91e8

I like Punkkills Micro 105 FPV Quadrocopter design (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1221911) and I wanted to build one. But in Germany you need special frequences for RC flighing which are not covered by the Micro Scisky or the Eachine Flight Controllers with reveiver build-in. So I ordered a SP3Racing Evo with a separate RM receiver from banggood. They send me a SPRacingEvo V2.0 which has outputs for six motors. So I decided to build up a hexacopter. Here is the printable design for it:

What you need:
frame (3D printed): HexaFrame.stl
top (3D printed): TopV2_05.stl or TopV1_04.stl
optional: Flightcontroller Case: FCCase.stl

6x brushed motors 8.5 mm (3x clockwise, 3x counterclockwise)
(https://www.banggood.com/Eachine-Tiny-QX90-Micro-FPV-Racing-Quadcopter-Spare-Parts-8_5x20mm-Coreless-Motor-p-1079157.html)

FrSky Ultra Light XM Receiver Up To 16CH (https://www.banggood.com/FrSky-XM-2_4G-16CH-Telemetry-Receiver-p-1107435.html)
or
Frsky XM+ Micro D16 SBUS Full Range Receiver Up to 16CH
(https://www.banggood.com/Frsky-XM-Micro-D16-SBUS-Full-Range-Receiver-Up-to-16CH-p-1110020.html

Micro 32bits F3 Brushed Flight Control Board Based On SP RACING F3 EVO Brush
(https://www.banggood.com/Micro-32bits-Brushed-Flight-Control-Board-Based-On-SP-RACING-F3-EVO-Brush-For-Micro-FPV-Frame-p-1070068.html)

5V Buzzer Alarm Beeper (https://www.banggood.com/3X-5V-Buzzer-Alarm-Beeper-With-Cable-for-QX70-QX90-QX95-NAZE32-F3-DIY-Micro-Brushed-FPV-Quadcopter-p-1118884.html)

LED Strip Light Board (https://www.banggood.com/Eachine-Tiny-QX95-Micro-FPV-Racing-Quadcopter-Spare-Parts-LED-Strip-Light-Board-QX95L-p-1093093.html)

Nylon Screws (https://www.banggood.com/180pcs-M3-Nylon-Black-Spacers-Screw-Nut-Hex-M-F-Stand-off-Assorted-Kit-Box-p-1000806.html)

Some connectors for easier build-up:
Excellway® 100Pcs Mini Micro JST 1.5mm ZH 2-Pin Connector Plug With Wires (https://www.banggood.com/100Pcs-Mini-Micro-JST-1_5mm-ZH-2-Pin-Connector-Plug-With-Wires-Cables-150mm-p-1170260.html)

Walkera QR Ladybird Blades Propellers (https://www.banggood.com/10X-Walkera-QR-Ladybird-Blades-Propellers-for-QX90-QX105-QX95-QX100-Hubsan-X4-DIY-Micro-Quadcopter-p-1196682.html)

For the FPV:
Super Mini Light AIO 5.8G 48CH 25mW VTX 520TVL 1/4 Cmos FPV Camera PAL/NTSC
(https://www.banggood.com/Super-Mini-Light-AIO-5_8G-48CH-200mW-VTX-520TVL-14-Cmos-FPV-Camera-PALNTSC-for-QX90-QX95-p-1095683.html)

I used Fatshark dominator V3 glasses with Nexwave 5G8 Race Band receiver module.

Instruction:
All parts printed in PETG from DasFilament in safety yellow color.
Infill: 25 %, no support
2 perimeters in vertical shell
2 perimeters in top and buttom shell

There are two versions of the top. One without cover for the camera (Top04), one with camera protection (TopV2_05).
The top parts get screwed together with the main frame with 20 mm nylon bolts and nuts as you can see on the pictures.
The flightcontroller can by glued with low temperature hotmelt glue into the optional flightcontroller case (Part PCCase) to obtain a better protection and stability.

Cut some 40-50 mm long pieces of the wired connector plugs and solder them to the motor cables. Don´t forget to isolate with heat-shrink tubing. Solder the JST 1.5mm ZH 2-Pin connectors to the motor outputs of the flight controller board (marked with M1 to M6). So the motors are easier to change in case of damage.

As firmware I used cleanflight.

One disadvantage of the design of the frame is, that the two rotors in front are always part of the video capture. So the frame has to be modified.

All these information come without any warrenty. Use this description at your own risk!

description.text:
*PLEASE READ NOTES BEFORE PRINTING!

This is my take on a teaching aid that I loved as a kid. It is similar to a set of Cuisenaire rods that are used for math instruction. Each rod segment is a cubic centimeter.

Notes:

PLEASE READ!

The rods can be printed as-is, but the box and cover will need to be slightly scaled up in the X and Y directions so that the rods are not too tightly held in the tray. I used a value of 100.5%, but even that was a little tight. I would suggest printing out the 10 centimeter rod first to use as a test and then print the scaled box to see how it fits in both directions. This also means that the box cover will need to be scaled to fit your scaled box but it's okay for that to be somewhat tight. (Sandpaper might be your friend here to get it just right)

There is a grid pattern in the floor of the box to allow the kids to position the rods to make patterns. When I printed it at 0.2mm resolution, the grid did not stick very well to the box. Some of the grid snapped off, but it was still very usable. If possible, try to print at a higher resolution to see if that helps the grid stick better as it will most likely be two print layers thick, instead of one. (If someone tries that, let me know if it really helps!)

I added holes to the box design to allow the rods to be pushed out from the bottom if they are tight, but I have not printed this version. (Let me know how it turns out!)

This guide clips onto the top of a Prusa i3 and prevents the filament from tugging against the sides of the spool when the X axis is near an extreme end and/or the spool is nearly empty.

Filament can be fitted into the guide even when it is already loaded into the extruder. Simply turn the inner guide so the slots lines up, insert the filament, then turn the inner guide to prevent the filament from escaping.

With a small piece of sponge or foam can be wrapped around the filament to further support it and a drop of oil can be added to smooth the filament's path through the extruder.

This guide can be used with any spool holder as it clips onto the Prusa independently but is best used with my Universal Spool Holder https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2504871. It is especially useful for guiding loose filament hung on my Loose Filament Holder https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2532195

Note: the two round holes in the back are for audo.... the cable from the speaker goes out then plugs back into the Rasbperry pi. It seemed an easy option to use headphones or speakers without any wiring.

Design note: It's hard to get the USB stick out... but you rarely have to. If you want to be able to remove it easily you can reorient the Pi to do so, add extensions for audo and power so that you can still run cables out the back. Just the same, you could get a USB extension and leave it be.

Base di supporto per le bobine del filamento. oltre alla stampa, sono necessari: due cuscinetti diametro interno 8, esterno 22, altezza 7; quattro viti M4 x 20: quattro dadi M4: un tubo di alluminio diametro interno 23 mm, lunghezza 100 mm. il montaggio non presenta problemi, unica accortezza, sarebbe quella di usare un bulino o punta per punzonare il tubo di alluminio in corrispondenza dei fori presenti sui tappi. non ho utilizzato delle viti, affinchè non siano presenti le teste delle viti, che potrebbero dar fastidio, in presenza di bobine lievemente più larghe. nulla vieta, se lo credete opportuno, di utilizzare ugualmente le viti. description.text:
Here is my solution for the Mini Talon Hatch. I wanted to use the pile of Hatch Latches we had on hand. These are the typical Canopy latch used on many 3D planes. Can be found HERE: http://www.ebay.com/itm/like/172552903900?chn=ps&dispItem=1

The fore end retains the wood block and can be used with a screw still if desired. I used (2) 1" pieces of .125" Fiberglass rod for my Pins.

The back end requires trimming and thinning the Hatch so that it sits nice and flush.

Print the Mini Talon Hatch Latch - Hatch Latch.STL top down. I chose to use some supports where the Latch Mechanism will fit in.

Print (2) Mini_Talon_HatchLatch-_Talon_sides.STL with the Posts pointing up. These stay put in the airframe very well with the posts acting as anchors. I press fit them to make a mark then used my solder iron to make a small hole. NOTE: The center hole is offset to the BOTTOM. This is important for the Latch side, as the latch lock is offset to the Bottom.

Print Mini_Talon_HatchLatch-_Hatch_Pins.STL for the front of hte Hatch to retain the Guide Pins. The holes are sized for Bamboo skewers, but I highly recommend .125" carbon or Fiberglass and resize the holes with a drill bit as necessary.

Bullet Kin enemy from Enter the Gungeon

I made the 3D model myself in Blender a while back since I was new to the program coming from 3DsMax and had it printed by my brother-in-law.
The feet aren't 100% accurate, but I modified them so he could stand on his own.
The 'cap' comes off also, like a plug, in order to hide a tiny gun when he's being displayed on his stand.

Speaking of the stand, the little stabilizing pin doesn't really work unless you print him larger, so sorry about that. I might get around to fixing it later, but I haven't yet, so it isn't too likely I will.

What did I do?

I made this guy around the time Enter the Gungeon was release as I was a huge fan of the game and my brother-in-law just got his 3D printer up and running.

Some of the other models of Bullet Kin that I found online were solid, increasing the build times and weight and causing imbalance in the figure. I decided to make my own and hollow him out and making the top removable.

I posted it on my blog, put the figure on my shelf, and promptly forgot about it for a while.

Now its ending up here because a fellow Gungeon fan messaged me asking if I could upload it, so here it is. :D

description.text:
Continuing on my bout of remixes, I've taken Matt Crotts' cavern river tiles and added OpenLOCK bases to them.

UPDATE: I am working on the thinner 5 mm rivers and will likely release them in October (2017). They will use a modified 2 mm thin OpenLock tab. I'll find out if these tabs are too thin to be useful.

Caveats: Due to the thickness of the OpenLOCK bases, the river bed currently sits at 7 mm instead of 5 mm. I like these kinds of tiles better when the river is significantly lower than the surrounding floor sections, so I might revisit this in the future.

It would mean that I'd have to use an alternative clip than OpenLOCK on the thin side of the river (perhaps a thin flat tab) and only use OpenLOCK on the sides that are thick. I'm considering future options, but for now it is what it is.

Because the river was raised, this also means the "peaks" of the tile are at 13 to 15 mm high. The flatter portions of the floor is 11 to 12 mm on average, so I would like to lower the profile of the whole tile by 2 mm... but again, that's long term.

comments.text: These are great, thanks very much!  Yes it would be tough to come up with some kind of hybrid base with half openlock and some other mechanism that could lock at a lower height, but I'm sure it could be done.
